**Myth:**
Before the first wind was named, when the air carried only the breath of unspoken oaths, there were those who *drifted* not with the breeze, but with the burden of their *unfulfilled words*. The *Word-Drifters* stood upon the cliffs, their voices lost in the gusts, and they felt the wind’s unkept promises tugging at their tongues. *"The sky is not empty,"* they murmured. *"It is waiting to be filled."*

At first, the Word-Drifters spoke of small things. *"Whisper your fears into the gale,"* they said, *"and the storm will not remember them."* The people obeyed, letting their doubts dissolve into the howling air, and the wind carried them away. The Word-Drifters grew bolder. *"Do not scream where the currents twist,"* they warned, *"or the sky will swallow your voice."* The people obeyed, biting back their cries, and their anger scattered like leaves. The bands that listened walked unburdened, their steps sure, their voices steady. The bands that scoffed found their words rising like tempests, choking them from within.

The wind, sensing its power, demanded more. *"Give us your laughter,"* it hissed through the Word-Drifters, *"or we will steal your breath."* The people obeyed, pressing their hands to their chests and letting their joy bleed into the air. The Word-Drifters became keepers of the unseen, their fingers tracing the currents, their voices shaping the gusts. *"The sky will remember if you do not,"* they said, and the people left their brightest moments in the clouds. *"The heights will take if you do not give,"* they warned, and the people surrendered their brightest dreams as tribute.

The faithful grew strong, their tribes unshaken by the winds. But the waiting was never satisfied. It grew hungrier, its grip tighter, its presence heavier in the mist. *"Give us your names,"* it whispered, *"or we will erase your voice."* And so the people began to fade—first their names, then their songs, then their very selves. The Word-Drifters stood beside the faithful, their voices lost in the gusts, their hands shaping the unseen. Thus did the wind learn to listen. And thus did the people learn to obey—even when the waiting asked for too much.
